Resumption of session
I declare resumed the session of the European Parliament that was adjourned on Friday 17 December, I again wish you all the best for the New Year and I hope that you had a good holiday.
As you can see, the dreaded "millennium bug" did not occur. However, citizens of some of our Member States have been the victims of terrible natural disasters.
Parliament would like to have a debate during this part-session over the next few days.
Today I would like to ask you - this is also the wish of some Members - to remember all the victims of the storms, especially in the various countries of the European Union, with a minute's silence.
I ask you to stand up to a minute's silence.
(Parliament rose to a minute's silence.)
Madam President, on a point of order.
As I am sure you know from the press and television, there have been several bomb explosions in Sri Lanka with numerous deaths.
Mr Kumar Ponnambalam, who only paid a visit to the European Parliament a few months ago, is one of the recent assassination victims in Sri Lanka.
Would it be appropriate if you, Madam President, wrote to the President of Sri Lanka expressing Parliament’s regrets for the violent death of Mr Ponnambalam and other Sri Lankan citizens and asking them to do all they can to help them to seek a peaceful solution to this very difficult situation?
Yes, Mr Evans, I think that such an initiative is quite appropriate.
If the House agrees, I will follow Mr Evans' suggestion.
Madam President, on a point of order.
Could you give me some information on Article 143, in relation to inadmissibility?
My question concerns a matter which will be raised on Thursday and to which I will refer again.
On Thursday Parliament will deal with the Cunha report on multiannual guidance programs, which proposes in paragraph 6 that countries that fail to meet their fleet reduction targets should be penalized annually with a kind of quota penalty.
Such penalties should be imposed despite the principle of relative stability.
I believe that the principle of relative stability is a fundamental legal principle of the common fisheries policy and that a proposal to undermine it would be legally inadmissible.
I would like to know whether it is possible to raise an objection to a document which is only a report and not a legislative proposal, and whether I have the power to do so on Thursday.
Just then, if you want, you can raise this question, i. H. on Thursday at the start of the debate on the report.
