work schedule
The next item is the examination of the final draft agenda as agreed by the Conference of Presidents on Thursday 13 January under Rule 110 of the Rules of Procedure.
There are no changes for Monday and Tuesday.
For Wednesday:
The Socialist Group has asked for a statement from the Commission on its strategic objectives for the next five years and on the Commission's administrative reform to be included on the agenda.
I would ask the applicant, Mr Barón Crespo, to justify his request if he so wishes.
Then we proceed as usual: one speaker for, one against.
Madam President! The presentation of the political program of the Prodi Commission for the entire parliamentary term was based on a proposal by the Group of the Party of European Socialists, which was unanimously approved by the Conference of Presidents in September and also by President Prodi, who made his inaugural address affirmed.
This commitment is important insofar as the Commission is an institution which, under the Treaties, has a monopoly of initiative and thus fundamentally shapes the political and legislative activities of this Parliament over the next five years.
I would also like to remind you that this Parliament expressed its confidence in President Prodi twice in the previous parliamentary term; of that parliamentary term it again trusted him in July and then, when the new Commission was in office, there was another vote of confidence in the Commission as a whole in September.
So the Commission has already had enough time to draw up its program and we have had enough time to get to know it and explain it to the citizens.
With this in mind, I would like to remind you of the resolution of September 15, which recommended that the proposal be tabled as soon as possible.
The events of the past week - which began on the fringes of the Conference of Presidents and where this conference was only used to confirm and ratify decisions taken outside of it - illustrate a dilemma: Either the Commission is unable to present this program (In in this case she should clarify.
According to its President, it is capable of doing this.
Since the Commission is represented by the Vice-President, Mrs de Palacio, I think it would be useful to find out, before the vote, the position of the Commission on its willingness to present the program as agreed.), Or Parliament is unable to test this program, as some seem to pretend.
In my view, this second hypothesis would be tantamount to renouncing our responsibility as Parliament and, moreover, to throwing up an original thesis, an unknown method, which would consist in giving the political groups the programmatic speech of the Commission in writing a week in advance - and not how agreed to give notice the day before - bearing in mind that the legislative program would be discussed in February so that we could dispense with the debate, since the press and the Internet would have informed all citizens of it the next day and Parliament no longer had any reason to consider the matter.
Since my group believes that a Parliament is there to listen, debate and reflect, we do not think there is any reason to justify this delay and we believe that if the Commission is able to do so, then we are right The time to put the original agreement between Parliament and the Commission back into force and to be able to approach our fellow citizens responsibly.
That is why the proposal by the Group of the Party of European Socialists, which you mentioned, is to keep Wednesday as the date for the presentation of the Prodi Commission program for the parliamentary term and to include the administrative reform project in that program, otherwise we will find ourselves in a paradoxical situation The excuse that the wording is not available would, on the one hand, deny the President of the Commission the right to speak in this Parliament and, on the other hand, a debate on the reform would take place without this Parliament being able to read the texts beforehand the debate.
I would therefore ask you, Madam President, to ask the Commission to give its opinion now and then to vote.
